Title:
Windows Drivers Reverse Engineering Methodology

Type:
Blog Post

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
This post documents a practical methodology for reverse engineering Windows WDM kernel drivers to identify attack surface and assess exploitability. It walks through setting up a modern kernel-debugging lab (WinDbg Preview + VM debuggee) with symbols and NET-based KD, then reviews driver fundamentals (DriverEntry, device objects/symlinks, IRP major functions, and IOCTL dispatching). Using MSI Afterburner’s RTCore64.sys as a case study, it shows how to statically map IOCTL codes to code paths in IDA and dynamically validate behavior via WinDbg breakpoints. The author leverages Driver Buddy Reloaded (IDA Python plugin) to automate IOCTL decoding and highlight risky APIs/opcodes, and uses IOCTLpus to craft DeviceIoControl requests and observe buffer/register influence. A key example traces IOCTLs reaching `wrmsr`/`rdmsr` and discusses MSR abuse potential (e.g., LSTAR syscall target overwrite) while noting practical constraints (blacklists, admin-only access, hypervisor MSR filtering, VBS). Useful for kernel exploit dev, driver vuln research, and defenders auditing signed third-party drivers.

Technical Focus:
- Windows kernel debugging over NET (WinDbg/KD, symbols, bcdedit dbgsettings)
- WDM driver architecture (DriverEntry, DEVICE_OBJECT, symlinks, IRP dispatch)
- IOCTL reverse engineering and decoding (METHOD_BUFFERED/METHOD_NEITHER, access flags)
- IDA Pro static analysis + automation (Driver Buddy Reloaded)
- Dynamic analysis with breakpoints and rebasing for KASLR
- Dangerous primitives in drivers (wrmsr/rdmsr, MmMapIoSpace) and exploitability constraints

Use Cases:
- Reverse engineer third-party/signed Windows drivers to enumerate IOCTL attack surface
- Map DeviceIoControl inputs to kernel code paths for fuzzing and vuln discovery
- Validate suspected vulnerable paths with live kernel debugging and register/buffer tracing
- Triage drivers for high-risk functionality (MSR access, physical memory mapping)
- Build reproducible kernel RE labs for training or research

Keywords:
Windows kernel, WDM, kernel driver, WinDbg Preview, kernel debugging, KDNET, bcdedit, _NT_SYMBOL_PATH, PDB symbols, IDA Pro, DriverEntry, IRP_MJ_DEVICE_CONTROL, IOCTL, DeviceIoControl, METHOD_BUFFERED, METHOD_NEITHER, IoCreateDevice, IoCreateSymbolicLink, KASLR, wrmsr, rdmsr, MSR, LSTAR, MmMapIoSpace, OSR Driver Loader, IOCTLpus, Driver Buddy Reloaded, VBS, hypervisor MSR filtering